#X text 175 342 reference;
#X text 286 298 We need ti have a reference point and we have a track amount which means how much of the pitch difference is used to control something. In this example we're doing something funny \, which is changing the tracking amount to cnotrol the pitch itself \, so we're distorting it., f 37;
#X text 188 447 With the difference in semiton we convert it to cents by multiplying to 100 \, but this can also be considered the tracking amount percentage. Then we convert to ratio and use it as an interval on the reference point., f 47;
#X text 48 24 We'll actually get back to this \, but it's nice to introduce this idea right here. Of course we have a basic usage of a keyboard MIDI input to control the pitch \, but we might want to control other things on the patch depending on the note input region. A classic example is controlling the cutoff of a filter \, but you can also think of envelope time \, LFO speed and any sort of modulation or parameter that shapes your sound and you want different behaviour or character depending on the pitch region., f 67;
